We treat the 2 boys sitting next to each other as a single unit, and thus we have 7 units to arrange.  There are $7!$ ways to arrange these units.  Within the unit, the boys can be arranged in $2!$ ways.  So there are $7! \cdot 2! = \boxed{10080}$ ways.ลื
From the list of answers in the book, we see that $(7 \cdot 1)(2 \cdot 1) = 14 \cdot 2 = \boxed{28}$ is the answer.神
The discrepancy is in the list of possible arrangements.  The three cases above are correct, but they are overcounted, since we have counted each arrangement twice.  We must divide each case by 2 to correct this.ถูก
Alternatively, we can treat the two boys as a single "super" boy, and there are 6! of these arrangements, because we are arranging 7 units.  Each super boy can be arranged in 2 ways (boy 1 and boy 2 or boy 2 and boy 1).  So there are $6! \cdot 2 \cdot 2 = 360 \cdot 4 = \boxed{1440}$ arrangements of the children.ที่เรา
It does not matter which boy and which boy sit together -- for example, it is perfectly acceptable for the two boys to sit on either end of the row, as in the third case above.เด็ก
From the list of answers in the book, the answer is again $10080.$沈
In general, this method is used when we want to avoid overcounting, when the boys and girls can be arranged in different ways -- for example, whether they sit next to each other or not.串
It is not usually necessary to worry about overcounting, unless the answer we are seeking is not among the answers in the book, in which case the first method above may prove useful.pósito
