We have a total of six gold medals to arrange in a row and we want to place two of them. However, because there are only two medals of each type (gold and honor) and they are indistinguishable, we can only arrange the gold medals by considering the pairs that we arrange. For each of the six gold medals, there are three ways of arranging a gold and a honor medal, so our total answer is $3^6=\boxed{729}$.วงศ์
To see why this is correct, we can consider the following: if we are to arrange the gold and honor medals for medal 1, there are three gold and three honor. In a similar manner, if we are to arrange the gold and honor for medal 2, we only have three ways to choose: one gold and two honors, one honor and two golds, and no medals at all. Finally, if we are to arrange the gold and honor for medal 3, we still have three possibilities. The same for the other medals. In other words, the same number of arrangements (three each for medal 1, 3 for medal 2, etc.) has to be assigned to each medal. This gives a total of $3^6=\boxed{729}$ distinct arrangements.อุปกร
The following image illustrates all possible arrangements. In the second picture, one medal is marked red, a second medal is marked green, and the rest are marked blue. (The gold medals are not shown in blue.) Finally, the third picture shows two medals that are gold and two that are honor. Finally, we must point out that the order of the medals is important in this solution. The order of the medals will be different in different arrangements. For example, the order of the two gold medals in the first arrangement is different from the order of the two gold medals in the second arrangement. In other words, we cannot just arrange the medals in a row and then order the gold and honor medals. (A similar problem was originally in an IMO problem in 1956.)อีเมล
