Note that the equation $r^2=4r^3$ is equivalent to $\frac{r^2}{r^3}=4$, which simplifies to $\left(\frac1r\right)^3=4$. Thus, $\left(\frac1r\right) = \sqrt[3]{4}$. The negative square root is not valid, so $\frac1r = \sqrt[3]{4}$. Thus, $r=1/\sqrt[3]{4}$, but the units on $r$ are units. Thus, we want the value of $\frac1{\sqrt[3]{4}}$. In short, we need a value of $r$ whose cube is 4 and whose reciprocal is $\sqrt[3]{4}$. We have $\left(\frac12\right)^3=4/8$, which is clearly not equal to 4, and so we can't get $\frac1r=\sqrt[3]{4}$ with a real value for $r$. The negative square root of 4 is also negative, so we have a negative volume. To confirm that the radius is $\frac1{\sqrt[3]{4}}$, we note that the positive and negative cubes cancel when we take reciprocals, and because $\sqrt[3]{-4}= \sqrt[3]{-1}\cdot\sqrt[3]{4}$ is negative, this is what we had wanted. So $\boxed{\frac1{\sqrt[3]{4}}}$ is the radius of the sphere.ปรับปรุง
