Because the tetrahedron is equilateral with side length $2$, if we cut a plane through the tetrahedron and the midpoint of $AB$ parallel to $AB$ and $CD$ at distance $d$ from $AB$ we get an octahedron with side length $2-d$, and similarly if we cut the tetrahedron parallel to $CD$ and $AD$ at distance $d$ from $AD$ we get an octahedron with side length $2-d$ as well. Therefore, the resulting octahedrons share the same area of the tetrahedron, so it is enough to find the surface area of one of them and multiply the result by 2. The surface area of an octahedron with side length $2-d$ is $(2)(3)(6)\left((2-d)^2/2\right)=18\left((2-d)^2-3\right)$. Evaluating the difference gives 10, so the surface area of one of these pieces is $180$ square units. Therefore the surface area of both pieces is $\boxed{360\text{ square units}}$. เพื่อ
