Note that the transformation matrix $\mathbf{M}$ can be found by computing the column vectors of the matrix. That is, $\mathbf{M}$ is given by
\[\mathbf{M} = \begin{pmatrix} 7 & 2 \\ -1 & -3 \end{pmatrix}.\]We want to transform the line $y = mx + b$ to $y = -\frac{3}{2} x + 1.$  This is equivalent to finding the column vectors of the matrix $\mathbf{M}^{-1}$ (in this order, but if this is not obvious, look at the last row of the inverse of $\mathbf{M}$ from the first row of the matrix, which is the row vector $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}$ and the second row of the matrix is the row vector $\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ after multiplying by $\mathbf{M}.$  It will be a row vector representing the column vectors of $\mathbf{M}^{-1}.$)  Then the inverse of $\mathbf{M} = \begin{pmatrix} 7 & 2 \\ -1 & -3 \end{pmatrix}$ is $\mathbf{M}^{-1} = \frac{1}{20} \begin{pmatrix} -3 & -2 \\ 1 & 7 \end{pmatrix}.$  Thus, the inverse matrix is
\[\mathbf{M}^{-1} = \begin{pmatrix} -3/20 & -1/10 \\ 1/20 & 7/20 \end{pmatrix}.\]Therefore, the transformed line is
