\begin{align*}
2x &= 3y = -z = t, \\
6x &= -y = -4z = s.
\end{align*}Then $t = 3s,$ so $s = -\frac{3t}{4} = \frac{9t}{16}.$  Hence, $(x,y,z) = (\frac{t}{2}, \frac{t}{3}, -t).$  This means the two lines have direction vectors
\[\left<\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{3}, -1\right> \text{ and }\left<\frac{1}{4}, -\frac{1}{2}, \frac{3}{4}\right>,\]respectively.  The angle between these vectors is
\[\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\frac{1}{8}}{\sqrt{\frac{13}{12}} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{13}{12}}} = \frac{1}{8}\right),\]which is $90^\circ.$  Thus, the lines are at an angle of $\boxed{90^\circ}.$
