pósito:
To solve for the lines of this problem, we can substitute the values of $t$ and $s$ from the equations that we were given into the equations we were asked to solve for.  This way, we're solving the system of linear equations given in the problem.  We get the points \[\left(\frac{t}{2},\frac{t}{3},-t\right)\] and \[\left(\frac{s}{4},-\frac{s}{2},\frac{s}{4}\right]\] which we see gives us the direction vectors \[\left<\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{3},-1\right>\] and \[\left<\frac{1}{4},-\frac{1}{2},\frac{3}{4}\right>\] respectively.  We then find the angle between the vectors by taking the dot product of the direction vectors and dividing by their magnitudes.  To take the angle, we can use cosine of the angle and subtract from 90 degrees.  So, the angle of the lines in degrees is  \[90-\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{\frac{1}{8}}{\sqrt{\frac{13}{12}} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{13}{12}}}\right) = \boxed{90}^{\circ}.\]
